WEBVTT

00:00.898 --> 00:14.273
what powerful singing we began marching into war with King Alfred's battle hymn, and we ended in the fury of the storm, trusting the sweet, sustaining grace of Christ, and then everything in between.

00:14.293 --> 00:25.285
If you hold your Bible open to 2 Corinthians chapter 10, we come this morning to the next passage that we will take together, verses 7 through 11.

00:26.306 --> 00:29.650
Authority.

00:30.530 --> 00:35.999
Authority is a word for many that is a very yucky word.

00:36.960 --> 00:39.744
This is a word that gives instant backlash.

00:39.785 --> 00:46.094
We hear the word authority, and if we're not careful, we will instantly begin to stiffen our spines a bit.

00:46.155 --> 00:49.580
We'll begin to activate our defenses a bit.

00:50.541 --> 00:58.514
By and large, in a fallen world, we do not like authority unless we are in authority.

00:59.170 --> 01:05.616
And I believe that that is for one major reason with two underlying implications.

01:06.717 --> 01:11.842
Generally speaking, we do not like authority and the reason is sin, sin.

01:12.943 --> 01:28.178
First of all, we are sinners and we naturally repel against any authority but our own because we want to be in authority, a problem that goes all the way back to the garden.

01:28.546 --> 01:33.414
But secondly, not only are we sinners, but other people are sinners too.

01:33.474 --> 01:41.628
So we see the gross misuse of authority in the lives of other people that should be wielding it rightly.

01:41.648 --> 01:49.181
And so it makes us rightly so squeamish about submitting to authority when we see how it's misused.

01:49.501 --> 01:54.610
And certainly we have experienced this in the government and in the healthcare system through

01:54.850 --> 01:59.318
2020 and COVID in the years that follow as well as many other places in our life.

02:00.460 --> 02:15.846
If you grew up in what was truly an abusive home, you may have seen this misuse of authority in the worst of ways and maybe in an unhealthy church, maybe in an unhealthy work environment.

02:16.787 --> 02:20.754
There are extraordinary times when authority

02:20.962 --> 02:37.886
is grossly misused and when it must be disregarded, if not even opposed, and yet even then, as much as possible, we're long suffering with a default position to yield ourselves under authority, so long as we can.

02:38.848 --> 02:40.050
God created authority.

02:40.070 --> 02:41.311
God has authority.

02:41.351 --> 02:43.154
God delegates authority.

02:43.394 --> 02:49.904
in and of itself as a good and godly thing by the ultimate authority of God himself.

02:50.284 --> 02:58.377
And God gives us instructions, and not only instructions, but examples of how authority is to be used.

02:59.138 --> 03:09.994
The truth is every single one of us, children included, are not only under authority, and we all are under authority in one way or another.

03:10.035 --> 03:12.338
Every single one of us

03:12.450 --> 03:17.037
also are in authority, and one way or another.

03:18.259 --> 03:34.002
Take the smallest child, a little girl with her dolls, a little boy with his dump trucks, their room, and even the smallest child has some sense of the exercise of authority, and some obviously more than others.

03:35.444 --> 03:39.250
And when that authority is exercised according to the authority of God,

03:39.586 --> 03:42.570
the intent is for the good and flourishing of those who are under it.

03:42.870 --> 03:46.775
Webster's 1828 dictionary defines authority simply this way.

03:47.175 --> 03:50.479
It's a right to command our act.

03:50.499 --> 03:57.808
Jesus himself was asked in Matthew 21, by what authority do you do these things?

03:58.929 --> 04:08.201
And he answered with a great commission in Matthew 28 by saying, all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me.

04:08.441 --> 04:09.362
Jesus said,

04:10.658 --> 04:15.245
In 2 Corinthians chapter 10, we see the proper use of authority.

04:16.006 --> 04:19.871
The title of today's sermon is for building up and not tearing down.

04:19.931 --> 04:38.258
And the interesting thing about today's sermon is that it is highly likely that every single person in this room will be hearing a sermon on 2 Corinthians chapter 10 verses seven through 11 for the first time in their entire life.

04:39.010 --> 04:44.300
When was the last time you heard a sermon exclusively devoted to these verses?

04:45.021 --> 04:53.377
And let's just be honest, there's a good chance that this will be the last time in your life that you hear a sermon exclusively devoted to these verses.

04:54.780 --> 05:02.354
Unless you have been just reading and studying through the Bible, expositionally in a Bible study or listening to a sermon series,

05:02.466 --> 05:12.638
These are very glossed over passages by which even the greatest of expositors just lump them into a larger section and then completely overlook them.

05:13.839 --> 05:21.689
And I believe that we find in the most unsuspecting of places, and God's holy word, the greatest of treasures.

05:22.770 --> 05:25.974
And this before us is one of those chests.

05:27.095 --> 05:29.778
I want you to back up just a little bit in your Bibles.

05:30.946 --> 05:45.085
What you have here is granddaddy Paul, their father in the faith personally and passionately coming to them, urging this church that he has preached the gospel to and has helped formed from the very beginning.

05:46.027 --> 05:54.639
If you look with me in your Bible, then 2 Corinthians 10 in the opening verses, we saw last week that he's coming to them with a meekness and gentleness of Christ.

05:55.420 --> 05:59.986
We read earlier in 2 Samuel 22, where

06:00.386 --> 06:01.347
It was sung.

06:01.427 --> 06:06.833
It was recited that it was your gentleness, Lord, that made me great.

06:07.974 --> 06:12.178
And so Paul comes to them with the weakness and gentleness of Christ.

06:12.478 --> 06:27.794
What we see in Paul's life is that there are times when he comes to the church, when he comes to the authorities assertively and he's acting like a lion with authority, he's bringing down the hammer and he's

06:28.098 --> 06:31.384
not only bring in a rod, but he's disciplining his children in love.

06:32.306 --> 06:46.994
But other circumstances, such as the one before us, present a picture where Paul is very patient, very gentle, graciously showing forth humility and love and pleading, probably through tears.

06:48.257 --> 06:51.122
The backdrop to what is before us

06:52.002 --> 06:58.472
clearly is adversaries in Paul's life who are casting him as weak and as dishonorable.

06:58.833 --> 07:06.806
We know in 1 Corinthians 9 that because he refused full-time support from the church, they talked as if Paul was illegitimate as a minister.

07:07.767 --> 07:14.418
We'll see this morning that it was his lack of eloquent speech referenced again in chapter 11 verse 6 that

07:14.594 --> 07:17.278
they used to undermine his credibility.

07:17.719 --> 07:22.606
And supposedly he did not bring the right letters of commendation in chapter three, verse one.

07:23.107 --> 07:28.054
Possibly he was accused in verse chapter 12 of not bringing mighty works.

07:28.074 --> 07:36.948
And then we'll see Lord willing in chapter 12 where they possibly undermine him for not having visions which Paul will address.

07:38.009 --> 07:41.074
So Paul is coming to this church for a third visit.

07:41.346 --> 07:49.957
And we saw last week that he's coming to a very arrogant people by and large, and he comes to see not their talk, but their power.

07:51.138 --> 07:59.008
Because Paul said in 1 Corinthians that the kingdom of God does not consist of tall, but the demonstration of power and authority.

08:00.009 --> 08:04.815
And he's pleading with them in this section of Corinthians to humble their hearts.

08:05.135 --> 08:10.642
He does not want to have to come to them boldly to confront them, but he will.

08:11.170 --> 08:16.376
And yet he takes no joy in doing that, just as no one should look forward to confrontation.

08:18.039 --> 08:21.823
And Paul certainly does not, but he's ready to bring it when it's necessary.

08:21.863 --> 08:32.597
So it's this boldness, it's this confidence that we see referenced here that Paul plans to show those who are accusing him of walking according to the flesh.

08:33.117 --> 08:36.421
He says in chapter 10 of undermining his ministry.

08:36.742 --> 08:40.146
And when he returns, he will discipline them

08:40.322 --> 08:43.967
with severity if there is not repentance.

08:43.987 --> 09:00.288
So all throughout Second Corinthians, Paul has put in the most uncomfortable position of having to defend his own calling and his own credibility, which is something no sane wants to do because Proverbs says, let another man speak well of you and not yourself.

09:01.189 --> 09:04.914
But it's this apostolic authority that is

09:05.090 --> 09:12.539
that is grounding his faithful ministry, which their salvation and their sanctification are pivoting on.

09:12.579 --> 09:16.583
So they need to receive Paul because of the ministry of God that he brings.

09:17.504 --> 09:22.991
Instead, the church is being confused by the smear campaign that's being brought against him.

09:24.032 --> 09:32.882
So what you see in the life of Jesus is what you tend to see, I believe, in the life of Paul, where the heart is very hard, you bring the hammer of God's law,

09:33.218 --> 09:35.361
and the demands of God's law to humble it.

09:35.622 --> 09:41.270
And where the heart is humble, you show tenderness and grace to build it back up in truth.

09:42.632 --> 09:49.722
Look with me in verse four, we saw last week where Paul asserts that our weapons are divinely powerful, they're mighty.

09:50.624 --> 09:53.828
The Bible says to destroy strongholds or fortresses.

09:54.810 --> 10:03.122
These are spiritual weaponry that God has given us that far exceed that of any earthly weapon, any

10:03.330 --> 10:05.594
any human apparatus.

10:06.576 --> 10:09.201
And Paul says God has made this freely ours.

10:10.364 --> 10:14.031
He says through Alcaridians that he may have come to them in weakness.

10:14.091 --> 10:20.423
He may have come to them in simplicity, but Paul is armed with the power of God.

10:20.684 --> 10:23.890
He has the gravitas of God on his life.

10:24.834 --> 10:35.624
And in his way, what you see as a result of his ministry is a trail of transformed lives who have submitted themselves and been changed by the power of God.

10:37.326 --> 10:50.318
Jeremiah chapter 1, 10, possibly being referenced in the background as Paul writes this, speaks of the Lord's word coming through his servant, both to destroy and overthrow as well as to build and to plan.

10:51.460 --> 10:54.002
And there is a major building project before us.

10:54.466 --> 11:05.884
Look with me in verse five, we saw the call to capture every worldly ideology, every personal soul that sets itself up against the knowledge of God.

11:05.905 --> 11:15.200
And I mentioned, and I want to make the point again, I really do believe by and large that the Christian life is one or lost in the mind.

11:15.240 --> 11:21.650
The things that we allow to enter our mind and then live there rent free.

11:22.626 --> 11:39.049
And Paul says anything that sets itself up against the knowledge and fear of God in prison and take it captive, make it a prisoner or war and say you are not welcome here and don't entertain it, treat it like an enemy, an enemy of God.

11:40.110 --> 11:48.882
Repent of it, refuse to entertain that error, turn our thoughts to the obedience of Christ, replace them with truth and with obedience.

11:50.850 --> 11:57.477
And this is a problem that goes all the way back to the garden, doubting God's word, did God really say?

11:57.537 --> 12:02.542
And it's lingering all throughout 2 Corinthians and in your life and mind today.

12:03.783 --> 12:06.365
Look with me in verse six, because we cut it short last week.

12:06.666 --> 12:09.048
Paul comes back now with very strong language.

12:09.068 --> 12:10.249
He says, being ready.

12:10.289 --> 12:15.054
The word for ready is a term used of military preparedness.

12:15.915 --> 12:19.218
It speaks of that, which is tactical and strategic.

12:20.034 --> 12:23.899
being ready to punish every disobedience.

12:24.800 --> 12:37.937
Paul is ready to come and punish every disobedience, likely every defiance against his faithful ministry and what he is putting forth in this letter of 2 Corinthians, not to mention 1 Corinthians.

12:38.918 --> 12:41.321
How would Paul punish every disobedience?

12:42.082 --> 12:48.210
He doesn't say, but when we read other parts of the New Testament, clearly that would invoke church discipline.

12:48.802 --> 13:07.711
He would expose their true colors publicly before the church in a situation like this one and then he would bring needed discipline to the saints and he would call on them to repent and he would rebuke everywhere needed and he would drive out the wolves without a second thought.

13:08.933 --> 13:17.426
But look with me in verse six, he says, when you're, I believe speaking to the saints in the church that are confused,

13:18.498 --> 13:26.149
When your obedience, likely your obedience to all that he's writing right here in 2 Corinthians, it's complete.

13:26.209 --> 13:30.235
Or the King James says, fulfilled, fulfilled.

13:31.477 --> 13:41.732
He says in 2 Corinthians 2, 9 that he wrote to them because he's testing them to see if they would be obedient in everything, which is the story of our lives.

13:42.994 --> 13:48.242
At Titus in 2 Corinthians 7 is recalling the obedience of them

13:48.418 --> 13:54.706
All, not just that they would be here, but doers of the word in every way.

13:55.928 --> 14:06.602
So writing to this confused church, now Paul seems to long for the saints' obedience and he's patient enough to anticipate the true colors of the false teachers to come to light.

14:07.783 --> 14:10.166
I love how one pastor summarized this verse.

14:10.186 --> 14:16.114
Listen, he said, the competent soldier understands the crucial importance of timing.

14:16.770 --> 14:23.480
Rather than fire blindly and risk killing friendly troops, he waits until the enemy is clearly in sight.

14:24.282 --> 14:28.628
Paul had the courage and the competence to punish all disobedience in Corinth.

14:29.349 --> 14:37.682
He would not allow the purveyors of error to destroy the church, but he also had the discipline to wait until the church's obedience was complete.

14:38.503 --> 14:45.394
Paul would not unleash his formidable apostolic power on anyone until each had taken his stand.

14:45.826 --> 14:49.612
That way, he would be clear who accepted the truth and who rejected it.

14:50.473 --> 14:58.365
Paul would be compassionate to the former, but to the latter would find him to be a courageous and highly competent opponent.

14:59.967 --> 15:12.786
And so that sets the stage as we begin to ease in to verses 7 through 11, where I want you to see in the passage before us five aspects of authority that Paul displays in the church.

15:14.114 --> 15:19.420
First of all, we see in verse seven, authority that is secure in Christ and not selfish and motive.

15:20.922 --> 15:26.228
In verse eight, we see authority that is assertive and not arrogant.

15:26.248 --> 15:30.793
In verse eight, the latter part, we see authority that builds up and doesn't tear down.

15:32.395 --> 15:38.642
In verses nine through 10, I want you to see authority that puts terror in your enemies and loving respect in your people.

15:39.554 --> 15:45.201
And fifthly, authority that is spoken and acted upon in verse 11.

15:45.221 --> 15:54.031
I want you to walk with me, first of all, in verse seven, where we see authority that is secure and not selfish in motive.

15:55.232 --> 16:00.118
Look in verse seven, Paul just puts it right out there in this passionate appeal.

16:01.059 --> 16:03.822
Look at what is before your eyes.

16:05.144 --> 16:07.026
Look at what is before your eyes.

16:07.810 --> 16:09.231
Now scholars are conflicted.

16:09.291 --> 16:13.636
This could be an indicative, which refers to what they're doing.

16:13.696 --> 16:15.998
They're looking at is what is before their eyes.

16:17.139 --> 16:21.844
And Paul could be saying, look rightly at what is truly before your eyes.

16:22.244 --> 16:27.149
Look at what is so plain before you that you need to see it, but obviously miss.

16:28.910 --> 16:30.232
It could be an interrogative.

16:30.712 --> 16:32.134
This also could be a question.

16:32.174 --> 16:36.658
Are you looking merely at what is before your own earthly eyes?

16:37.922 --> 16:45.573
Or maybe it's an imperative, as it is represented in the ESV, you need, you must look at what is before your eyes.

16:47.236 --> 17:02.738
Paul might be referring to 1 Samuel 16, seven, when Samuel was told by the Lord, when you go to choose the king of Israel, do not look merely at earthly outward appearances.

17:03.106 --> 17:06.370
Don't just look at height, don't just look at stature.

17:06.390 --> 17:10.496
Don't just look for a man who has sculpted like a Greek God.

17:10.536 --> 17:20.490
But what I want you to do is look at heart, look at character, look at inner fortitude, look and see if this man is anchored in his convictions to God.

17:20.530 --> 17:24.035
And so that could be what Paul is saying here.

17:24.395 --> 17:29.522
Either way, John 724 says, do not judge by appearances.

17:30.690 --> 17:33.474
but judge with right judgment.

17:34.395 --> 17:38.581
How many times have you heard the verse from unbelievers who've read no other verse in the Bible?

17:39.482 --> 17:42.467
Judge not, judge not.

17:43.929 --> 17:53.542
And yet the Bible says, no, you mechanic must judge, but don't just judge a book by its color or it's covered judge with a righteous judgment.

17:54.684 --> 17:56.005
Judge with a righteous judgment.

17:56.987 --> 17:59.250
So most likely, Paul here in verse seven,

18:00.130 --> 18:05.136
seems to be calling on the church to look at what's plainly before them as God sees it.

18:06.117 --> 18:07.619
They're making such claims.

18:07.699 --> 18:08.440
What about us?

18:08.500 --> 18:17.831
Look in verse seven, if anyone is confident that he is Christ, let him remind himself that just as he is Christ, so also are we.

18:17.851 --> 18:26.081
These false teachers, like all false teachers, tend to be our boasting of some special relationship to Jesus Christ.

18:27.022 --> 18:30.066
Maybe they've had visions, maybe they've had

18:30.146 --> 18:32.769
some sort of insider knowledge.

18:33.169 --> 18:37.354
Maybe they're boasting of some Hyattistic communion with Christ.

18:37.414 --> 18:39.637
That would far outweigh what Paul could claim.

18:39.657 --> 18:45.463
And they're confident that they're Christ and they have this special relation to him.

18:45.523 --> 18:58.738
And yet Paul says, remind yourself that even as they claim that, wrongly so, remember that we do all the more, claim the same thing.

18:59.714 --> 19:07.185
1 Corinthians 9, 1, Paul says that he is an apostle because he's seen the risen Lord Jesus with his own eyes.

19:08.286 --> 19:12.152
Galatians 1, 12, Paul says, I didn't learn from men.

19:12.172 --> 19:20.604
I learned directly from Jesus Christ himself who appointed me as an apostle.

19:22.006 --> 19:27.794
So he mentions this confidence and Paul mentions confidence often in 2 Corinthians.

19:27.874 --> 19:40.876
boastful confidence, the confidence of his new covenant ministry, the confidence he says in chapter three, verse four, that was extended towards God through Christ.

19:42.138 --> 19:50.612
And yet there's a wrong founded confidence in his adversaries who are winning the hearts and affections of the church.

19:52.435 --> 19:54.258
In first Corinthians 14, Paul,

19:54.530 --> 19:58.776
calls on the church to acknowledge his writings as God's command.

20:00.038 --> 20:03.203
And first John 4, 6, he says, we are from God.

20:03.243 --> 20:06.948
And just as Jesus is sheep, here is voice.

20:08.230 --> 20:11.936
So his followers will listen to his word.

20:11.976 --> 20:17.724
First Corinthians 3, 23 says, and you are Christ and Christ is God.

20:18.646 --> 20:20.709
And so Paul says, we belong to Christ.

20:20.789 --> 20:22.531
We were divinely charged.

20:22.551 --> 20:24.274
And so we saints, we

20:25.058 --> 20:28.441
We are in Christ and we belong to Christ.

20:29.463 --> 20:41.135
So humble yourself before his word, before faithful ministry, authority that is securing Christ and not selfish and motive as we see in the false teachers.

20:42.596 --> 20:43.036
Look at me.

20:43.077 --> 20:52.306
Secondly, in verse eight, we move now to another truth about authority in this passage, authorities, which Paul

20:53.442 --> 20:59.831
uses authority that is assertive and not arrogant, assertive and not arrogant.

21:00.132 --> 21:10.346
He writes in verse 8, for even if I boast a little too much, or it could read, even if I boast somewhat more, i.e.

21:10.366 --> 21:15.974
than the false teachers of our authority, he goes on and he says, I will not be ashamed.

21:17.296 --> 21:21.362
Over and over, Paul uses this word boast in first and second Corinthians.

21:22.242 --> 21:25.826
Sometimes he uses it in the same way we think of it in a negative light.

21:26.187 --> 21:28.590
He uses it as those who are full of themselves.

21:29.671 --> 21:41.145
But other times Paul uses this word for boast in a positive way, as if boasting in the church, which is filled with the evidence of Christ, their lives exalting Christ.

21:41.786 --> 21:43.548
And Paul takes great pride in that.

21:43.588 --> 21:51.698
So if you'll look with me in verse eight, he says, even if I boast a little too much or somewhat more, there's a bashfulness.

21:52.354 --> 21:54.477
about boasting in his authority.

21:55.599 --> 22:07.879
And listen, anyone who walks around beating their chest, wanting everyone to know how much authority they have must first realize that they don't have the authority that they think they have, if they have to constantly remind people of it.

22:09.482 --> 22:10.603
And so there's a humility.

22:10.623 --> 22:19.698
There's a, there's a vastfulness about this where Paul is not wanting to assert himself, not wanting to remind them of who he is.

22:21.154 --> 22:26.924
And yet at the same time, he says, I can boast all the more than they do.

22:27.004 --> 22:28.586
And I would still not boast too much.

22:29.348 --> 22:33.434
That's the extent of authority that Paul has been given by God.

22:33.534 --> 22:36.079
And he concludes, I will not be ashamed to use it.

22:37.060 --> 22:47.858
I will not be ashamed to use it because it was given to him by God and he is using it not in a heavy handed way, but to build them up.

22:48.482 --> 23:01.260
And Paul always uses this authority when we see the gospel or when we see the integrity of the church at stake, you see a different side of him as a true and faithful shepherd.

23:01.581 --> 23:07.128
In verses 13, as well as in 15, if you'll look down, Paul says that he will not boast beyond limit.

23:07.349 --> 23:14.058
He will not extend himself beyond what he should.

23:14.078 --> 23:16.722
And so he's not ashamed.

23:17.186 --> 23:19.188
Maybe embarrassed to go beyond it.

23:19.208 --> 23:24.755
Maybe careful to be over heavy handed, but certainly not ashamed to rightly wield it.

23:24.775 --> 23:36.469
2 Corinthians 12, 7 says that God had sent Paul a messenger from hell to keep him from becoming conceited in his boasting.

23:37.410 --> 23:39.012
And doesn't the Lord do that in our lives?

23:40.273 --> 23:44.178
A thorn to keep us humbled before him.

23:44.994 --> 23:57.552
As I mentioned earlier, authority rightly assumed and used is a good and godly thing and it is not something to be ashamed of or repulsed by in God's good design.

23:59.054 --> 24:05.723
So what we see in Paul's life right here is that God has entrusted him both with authority and with responsibility.

24:07.426 --> 24:10.450
Now the problem oftentimes in the modern world

24:11.362 --> 24:22.096
whether it be in the family, whether it be in the church, whether it be in the workplace with masters and servants, or whether it be even in the community, civil sphere.

24:23.699 --> 24:38.098
A major problem that we have that Paul, I believe, at least in part, is cutting against is when you have a person that's given responsibility for a job, but they're not given the authority to carry out that job.

24:39.298 --> 24:49.833
And Paul has both and he is explaining both the authority that he has that he's not ashamed of and the responsibility to wield it, to build them up rightly.

24:51.455 --> 25:04.914
What you often find in our world today is maybe a pastor who's given a responsibility to shepherd, but not the authority of making and enforcing decisions.

25:05.122 --> 25:11.150
You see a man who's given responsibility to rule his house, but he's neutered of the authority to actually do it.

25:12.232 --> 25:31.538
You see, you see pseudo-parents who are giving children to take care of, and the responsibility to shepherd and care for those children, but they don't actually have the authority to parent those children, which is a real problem with modern daycares, and anyone who's worked in them knows that is the case.

25:32.674 --> 25:42.864
A person who's given responsibility in their workplace or at their office, but they're not given the authority needed to actually carry it out in a meaningful way.

25:44.645 --> 25:49.650
Friends, the most basic principle of authority in life is this.

25:50.771 --> 25:54.535
Authority flows to those who take responsibility.

25:55.496 --> 26:01.842
And Paul is taking responsibility for this flaw in the dirtiest and messiest of ways

26:02.530 --> 26:09.941
And then increasingly, we see that both stole on his shoulders authority to execute that responsibility.

26:11.403 --> 26:19.095
You see what we see flavors of throughout second Corinthians is that the lowest level of leadership is leadership by title.

26:20.136 --> 26:21.498
In other words, he's the expert.

26:21.518 --> 26:22.400
He has the credentials.

26:22.420 --> 26:25.725
He is so and so, so you need to do what he says.

26:27.127 --> 26:31.032
And Paul says, do I have to present letters of recommendation?

26:31.213 --> 26:32.114
Do I have to present?

26:32.450 --> 26:34.453
credentials and criteria to you.

26:35.935 --> 26:39.660
The highest level of leadership is not by title.

